<item>
            <title>[SPARK-33277] Python/Pandas UDF right after off-heap vectorized reader could cause executor crash.</title>
                <link>https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/SPARK-33277</link>
                <project id="12315420" key="SPARK">Spark</project>
                    <description>&lt;p&gt;Python/Pandas UDF right after off-heap vectorized reader could cause executor crash.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;E.g.,:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;code panel&quot; style=&quot;border-width: 1px;&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;codeContent panelContent&quot;&gt;
&lt;pre class=&quot;code-java&quot;&gt;
spark.range(0, 100000, 1, 1).write.parquet(path)

spark.conf.set(&lt;span class=&quot;code-quote&quot;&gt;&quot;spark.sql.columnVector.offheap.enabled&quot;&lt;/span&gt;, True)

def f(x):
    &lt;span class=&quot;code-keyword&quot;&gt;return&lt;/span&gt; 0

fUdf = udf(f, LongType())

spark.read.parquet(path).select(fUdf(&lt;span class=&quot;code-quote&quot;&gt;&apos;id&apos;&lt;/span&gt;)).head()
&lt;/pre&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p&gt;This is because, the Python evaluation consumes the parent iterator in a separate thread and it consumes more data from the parent even after the task ends and the parent is closed. If an off-heap column vector exists in the parent iterator, it could cause segmentation fault which crashes the executor.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
